In Brazil, the creation of the Unified Health System (SUS) stands out, as well as health guidance through the Family Health Strategy. In addition, other important policies in Brazil were as follows: Decree no. 5.659, the Picture-Convention on Control of Tobacco (CQCT, in Portuguese) in 2006;
                        21
                      Law no. 12.546, from 2011, which prohibited smoking in collective environments, increased taxes on cigarettes by 85% and established a minimum price for sales; Presidential Decree no. 8.262 from 2014, which increased warnings on cigarette packages and regulated smoke-free environments;
                        22
                      the 2006 Food guide for the Brazilian Population and its revision in 2014;
                        23
                      the Plan for Reducing Salt Consumption;
                        24
                      the organisation of the Risk Factor Surveillance and protection against NCDs since 2006;
                        25
                      as well as other health surveys, such as the National Health Survey in 2013
                        26
                      and the Plan for Strategic Actions to Combat NCDs in Brazil, 2011–2022.
